{"focus":{"id":"9a22162c-1b61-5d35-8ecc-0861f812544e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c7b3d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.A.1","description":"Verify experimentally the properties of dilations given by a center and a scale factor:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.A","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"bbc995ce-7cd3-59c6-896d-64a23b2ee989","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba09818-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.D.8","description":"Determine the unknown whole number in an addition or subtraction equation relating three whole numbers. *For example, determine the unknown number that makes the equation true in each of the equations $8 + ? = 11, 5 = \\Box  - 3, 6 + 6 = \\Box$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"1208a51d-bbaa-5d92-8192-758a71391c59","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba03a8f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.D.7","description":"Understand the meaning of the equal sign, and determine if equations involving addition and subtraction are true or false. *For example, which of the following equations are true and which are false? 6 = 6, 7 = 8 - 1, 5 + 2 = 2 + 5, 4 + 1 = 5 + 2.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"d865f537-3bc8-5143-81b9-3ade20de09d2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fd7e9-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.B.6","description":"Represent whole numbers as lengths from 0 on a number line diagram with equally spaced points corresponding to the numbers 0, 1, 2, …, and represent whole-number sums and differences within 100 on a number line diagram.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"40edda9b-7aed-5802-8bff-d566f71df50d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d400d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.NF.A.2","description":"Understand a fraction as a number on the number line; represent fractions on a number line diagram.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"NF","cluster":"3.NF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"c2e862e1-58f3-55fe-9d03-091c8275f77f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba04a80-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.MD.C.7","description":"Recognize angle measure as additive. When an angle is decomposed into non-overlapping parts, the angle measure of the whole is the sum of the angle measures of the parts. Solve addition and subtraction problems to find unknown angles on a diagram in real world and mathematical problems, e.g., by using an equation with a symbol for the unknown angle measure.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"MD","cluster":"4.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"53375445-0a44-5b95-a47d-fdb93e5b2298","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f6012-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.MD.C.5","description":"Recognize angles as geometric shapes that are formed wherever two rays share a common endpoint, and understand concepts of angle measurement:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"MD","cluster":"4.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"ba2855ee-89aa-5bf2-9741-b2ef8a53d122","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d5464-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.G.A.2","description":"Represent real world and mathematical problems by graphing points in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane, and interpret coordinate values of points in the context of the situation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"G","cluster":"5.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d34ac232-6f89-53d4-8281-35ae2a7126ff","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e3d90-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.G.A.3","description":"Draw polygons in the coordinate plane given coordinates for the vertices; use coordinates to find the length of a side joining points with the same first coordinate or the same second coordinate. Apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"G","cluster":"6.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"13602b07-ab55-571e-8540-d1049ab0a9ed","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d73cd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.G.A.2","description":"Draw (freehand, with ruler and protractor, and with technology) geometric shapes with given conditions. Focus on constructing triangles from three measures of angles or sides, noticing when the conditions determine a unique triangle, more than one triangle, or no triangle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"G","cluster":"7.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"1d0511f7-17b7-5468-85e9-5e282bc6f4d9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f7d68-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.G.B.5","description":"Use facts about supplementary, complementary, vertical, and adjacent angles in a multi-step problem to write and solve simple equations for an unknown angle in a figure.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"G","cluster":"7.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"cf8f294e-a741-5295-8441-39a8caeeb802","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e55c9-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.G.A.3","description":"Describe the effect of dilations, translations, rotations, and reflections on two-dimensional figures using coordinates.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"G","cluster":"8.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"785dbfaa-3ede-5681-91dc-23574d49a09e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c465b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.G.A.1","description":"Verify experimentally the properties of rotations, reflections, and translations:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"G","cluster":"8.G.A","level":"standard"}],"descendants":[{"id":"94e31f65-b9f8-5b66-a544-cb5531c798ab","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa05a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.5","description":"Given a geometric figure and a rotation, reflection, or translation, draw the transformed figure using, e.g., graph paper, tracing paper, or geometry software. Specify a sequence of transformations that will carry a given figure onto another.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4ec3730e-b586-58b1-ba65-dd85106e7481","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9db04d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.A.2","description":"Given two figures, use the definition of similarity in terms of similarity transformations to decide if they are similar; explain using similarity transformations the meaning of similarity for triangles as the equality of all corresponding pairs of angles and the proportionality of all corresponding pairs of sides.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a92e46a6-062f-571f-8176-2cae037da9d9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6ead-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.3","description":"Given a rectangle, parallelogram, trapezoid, or regular polygon, describe the rotations and reflections that carry it onto itself.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"80e2ab52-76b7-5dbc-a73e-49efe25ab94f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba011a4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.6","description":"Use geometric descriptions of rigid motions to transform figures and to predict the effect of a given rigid motion on a given figure; given two figures, use the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions to decide if they are congruent.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"a8d6cc3b-4205-5513-a948-c628938ab8c9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e7866-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.A.3","description":"Use the properties of similarity transformations to establish the AA criterion for two triangles to be similar.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"1278683e-82dc-5f9f-8ed9-19ef9f1a8846","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c6a73-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.1","description":"Prove that all circles are similar.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"8957175b-6ae1-533c-82e1-9059810669cb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f9d82-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.B.5","description":"Derive using similarity the fact that the length of the arc intercepted by an angle is proportional to the radius, and define the radian measure of the angle as the constant of proportionality; derive the formula for the area of a sector.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"6f7e8054-4156-5c2f-b56f-b65711cfc25f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba07418-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.7","description":"Use the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions to show that two triangles are congruent if and only if corresponding pairs of sides and corresponding pairs of angles are congruent.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e1140f7-e845-5ee7-8b94-abfcdce11415","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0c2a8-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.8","description":"Explain how the criteria for triangle congruence (ASA, SAS, and SSS) follow from the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"9cf05948-92aa-5ed5-8312-5d8cba784978","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f1e1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.9","description":"Prove theorems about lines and angles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"ec224230-3b80-5156-b6b2-82b68e282880","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f195e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.B.4","description":"Prove theorems about triangles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"9805c9cb-4725-5fbf-b0ba-ee33b666c18a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa609-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.B.5","description":"Use congruence and similarity criteria for triangles to solve problems and to prove relationships in geometric figures.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"09861714-4ec2-50fa-bd3a-b42ff30223ab","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba017c6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.C.6","description":"Understand that by similarity, side ratios in right triangles are properties of the angles in the triangle, leading to definitions of trigonometric ratios for acute angles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"fff120ce-1225-5947-ba41-aa83e8f29989","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c675d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.1","description":"Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"dfbae8ab-8976-5b42-8021-5b9ab891eb6e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9caa8d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.10","description":"Prove theorems about triangles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"d75cd0a8-4c34-5658-b919-fada1445f6cb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cb3ef-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.11","description":"Prove theorems about parallelograms.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"069ebfbe-44da-5805-b54e-1442936b729d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9da1fd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.2","description":"Identify and describe relationships among inscribed angles, radii, and chords.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"400c23e6-ef6b-5adf-8d27-64a4515bb8fd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6c76-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.3","description":"Construct the inscribed and circumscribed circles of a triangle, and prove properties of angles for a quadrilateral inscribed in a circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"5043f047-9f14-56fb-9c1f-e1d5c28af877","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0ef63-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.9","description":"(+) Prove the addition and subtraction formulas for sine, cosine, and tangent and use them to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"3bf30fb5-71d5-54fb-be47-574fb88880d0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa334-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.5","description":"Prove the slope criteria for parallel and perpendicular lines and use them to solve geometric problems (e.g., find the equation of a line parallel or perpendicular to a given line that passes through a given point).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1bb5899c-2929-5d5c-ad6d-44cdf5d736f2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba014b5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.6","description":"Find the point on a directed line segment between two given points that partitions the segment in a given ratio.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"2b599071-8547-5521-add4-18ee082a5d2a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d9f54-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.2","description":"Explain how the unit circle in the coordinate plane enables the extension of trigonometric functions to all real numbers, interpreted as radian measures of angles traversed counterclockwise around the unit circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"c19d1d86-6056-5558-82a1-e8bc0f04654b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0bf6b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.8","description":"Prove the Pythagorean identity $\\sin^{2}(\\theta) + \\cos^{2}(\\theta) = 1$ and use it to find $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ given $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ and the quadrant of the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"19f509d0-e076-586b-9ed7-86b863cec2da","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba07a82-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.C.7","description":"Explain and use the relationship between the sine and cosine of complementary angles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"7d4b0f0b-04e2-50aa-a0c1-0a690ded7b09","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0c5dc-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.C.8","description":"Use trigonometric ratios and the Pythagorean Theorem to solve right triangles in applied problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"628c4c0a-a399-5f03-b8d1-511667432206","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f473-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.D.9","description":"(+) Derive the formula $A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\sin(C)$ for the area of a triangle by drawing an auxiliary line from a vertex perpendicular to the opposite side.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"5ee2cead-ed7d-5d00-b4b1-0dd1b0fce583","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f0f18-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.4","description":"(+) Construct a tangent line from a point outside a given circle to the circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"64faff1c-68b2-5673-b552-23538ed39193","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa8da-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.B.5","description":"(+) Represent addition, subtraction, multiplication, and conjugation of complex numbers geometrically on the complex plane; use properties of this representation for computation. *For example, $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)^{3} = 8$ because $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)$ has modulus 2 and argument $120^{\\circ}$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"088892fa-d4c0-5124-bbda-72204983bd4f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f0c6f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.4","description":"(+) Use the unit circle to explain symmetry (odd and even) and periodicity of trigonometric functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4ace16fc-ec48-547d-8fe8-17bb9011e990","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f9a9b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.5","description":"Choose trigonometric functions to model periodic phenomena with specified amplitude, frequency, and midline.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"d0979cb7-6dd3-5950-9230-4dbf862eb0ee","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba00e93-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.6","description":"(+) Understand that restricting a trigonometric function to a domain on which it is always increasing or always decreasing allows its inverse to be constructed.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"4b576e40-8317-5342-99a9-f84b32754936","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6a3a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.3","description":"(+) Use special triangles to determine geometrically the values of sine, cosine, tangent for $\\frac{\\pi}{3}$, $\\frac{\\pi}{4}$ and $\\frac{\\pi}{6}$, and use the unit circle to express the values of sine, cosine, and tangent for $\\pi-x$, $\\pi+x$, and $2\\pi-x$ in terms of their values for x, where x is any real number.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"fa319b8b-ffac-571d-b9b8-067100764742","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cacdd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.D.10","description":"(+) Prove the Laws of Sines and Cosines and use them to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"31a025e7-5652-52ad-8220-e0dcd2669f3b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cb64c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.D.11","description":"(+) Understand and apply the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines to find unknown measurements in right and non-right triangles (e.g., surveying problems, resultant forces).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"b1e4c13f-eddc-544f-9fe8-7e372ba3e739","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba01ad6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.B.6","description":"(+) Calculate the distance between numbers in the complex plane as the modulus of the difference, and the midpoint of a segment as the average of the numbers at its endpoints.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"cc2355c0-fe93-597c-ae5d-cee6e823d018","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba070dd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.7","description":"(+) Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate the solutions using technology, and interpret them in terms of the context.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"}],"learningComponents":[{"id":"b83a894c-4043-5e3e-ae5f-d9479abc2d6a","description":"Verify experimentally the properties of dilations given by a center and a scale factor","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"}],"edges":[{"id":"eb732987-a154-5e88-9088-b0c631b35583","label":"buildsTowards","source":"1208a51d-bbaa-5d92-8192-758a71391c59","target":"bbc995ce-7cd3-59c6-896d-64a23b2ee989"},{"id":"624ca67a-4fe7-553e-8a16-9cfaeabe6374","label":"buildsTowards","source":"bbc995ce-7cd3-59c6-896d-64a23b2ee989","target":"c2e862e1-58f3-55fe-9d03-091c8275f77f"},{"id":"7c7f03d2-7561-5fb5-9e53-4c413c912879","label":"buildsTowards","source":"d865f537-3bc8-5143-81b9-3ade20de09d2","target":"40edda9b-7aed-5802-8bff-d566f71df50d"},{"id":"46fe802d-508c-5c91-9059-9138af6cec36","label":"buildsTowards","source":"40edda9b-7aed-5802-8bff-d566f71df50d","target":"ba2855ee-89aa-5bf2-9741-b2ef8a53d122"},{"id":"9a47bfd6-ce34-56bf-9e2a-a3ad905484a0","label":"buildsTowards","source":"533754